  I think the supreme court decision was the right one.  <br>
<br>
  First, keep in mind we are not talking about photographs of children, we are talking about drawn or rendered pictures of fictitious children.  There is no exploitation of a child that occurs, as there would be if you photographed a living person (ie, no child had sex or anything for the rendring or painting to occur).<br>
<br>
  The main argument against it is that it is deemed 'harmful' to peoples minds.  Perhaps it is my opinion that pictures of people shooting guns, driving fast, taking drugs, rioting, drinking, dancing in a disco are harmful.   Where do you draw the line, and who decides what is harmful from a drawing or painting?  We are talking about setting precedents for the reasoning that can be used to make future laws, and that would not be a good precedent to make.    <br>
<br>
The main thing that makes child porn illegal (and photos are still illegal) was the fact that a child had to be exploited to make it.  With a drawn or rendered picture this is not the case.  To say that people cannot see something because it might make a certain impression on them is dangerous ground.  It can and will be taken to the extreme if you set the precedent and say that type of logic can be used to make laws, so the court decision makes sense to me.<br>
<br>
